00:41:52.570 --> 00:41:54.690
A lot of stuff I
think that gets taught

00:41:54.690 --> 00:41:59.870
these days is computation,
because computation is easy.

00:41:59.870 --> 00:42:01.710
You can easily measure it.

00:42:01.710 --> 00:42:03.980
You can say, oh, did you
get the right number?

00:42:03.980 --> 00:42:05.239
It's like, well, OK.

00:42:05.239 --> 00:42:06.280
You got the right number.

00:42:06.280 --> 00:42:09.220
But that doesn't
give you much clue

00:42:09.220 --> 00:42:10.730
as to whether they
got any insight

00:42:10.730 --> 00:42:13.264
from getting that number,
which is a much harder problem.

00:42:13.264 --> 00:42:14.930
And I think that's
where the problem is.

00:42:14.930 --> 00:42:18.920
It's not so much that we
have bad teachers per se.

00:42:18.920 --> 00:42:22.090
It's that getting
people to get concepts

00:42:22.090 --> 00:42:24.770
is actually a very challenging
thing and a very, very

00:42:24.770 --> 00:42:26.230
hard thing to measure.

00:42:26.230 --> 00:42:30.140
And so, you've given as
you saidd-- your students

00:42:30.140 --> 00:42:33.320
with the lowest GPA's
the hardest problem.

00:42:33.320 --> 00:42:36.670
How do you measure how someone
else is going to succeed?

00:42:36.670 --> 00:42:38.615
Anyway, so just another--

00:42:38.615 --> 00:42:40.490
AUDIENCE: I had a
technical question for you.

00:42:40.490 --> 00:42:41.510
AVNER ASH: Yes, please.

00:42:41.510 --> 00:42:43.500
AUDIENCE: So the zeta functions.

00:42:43.500 --> 00:42:45.795
Because they involve greater
and greater exponents,

00:42:45.795 --> 00:42:49.000
does that lead to
faster converging

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:52.020
numerical estimations for pi?

00:42:52.020 --> 00:42:53.920
ROBERT GROSS: It would
except the power of pi

00:42:53.920 --> 00:42:55.240
is higher each time.

00:42:55.240 --> 00:42:57.130
And it turns out to
pretty much average out.

00:42:57.130 --> 00:42:57.838
AUDIENCE: Really?

00:42:57.838 --> 00:42:59.957
Because the square root
algorithms for example.

00:42:59.957 --> 00:43:00.790
ROBERT GROSS: Right.

00:43:00.790 --> 00:43:04.480
But the error seems to go--
if you compute zeta of 100

00:43:04.480 --> 00:43:06.794
and relate that
to pi to the 100.

00:43:06.794 --> 00:43:08.210
And then, take the
hundredth root,

00:43:08.210 --> 00:43:10.764
it's not the right
way to compute pi.

00:43:10.764 --> 00:43:13.180
There is a lot of number theory
involved in the right ways

00:43:13.180 --> 00:43:14.460
to compute pi.

00:43:14.460 --> 00:43:17.920
But the zeta function turns
out not to be a good way.

00:43:17.920 --> 00:43:20.260
It's very disappointing,
because you would only

00:43:20.260 --> 00:43:22.790
need to add one or two terms.

00:43:22.790 --> 00:43:25.000
AVNER ASH: But there's an
interesting separate issue

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:27.480
there that you raise.

00:43:27.480 --> 00:43:29.340
And I'm not an expert
on this, so I might

00:43:29.340 --> 00:43:30.660
say something that's incorrect.

00:43:30.660 --> 00:43:31.650
Maybe you can--

00:43:31.650 --> 00:43:37.140
But as Rob showed you,
zeta of even numbers--

00:43:37.140 --> 00:43:39.020
so those are the
reciprocals of squares,

00:43:39.020 --> 00:43:40.920
fourth powers, sixth powers.

00:43:40.920 --> 00:43:42.780
That infinite sum is known.

00:43:42.780 --> 00:43:45.990
It's a power of pi times a
rational number, it's easy.

00:43:45.990 --> 00:43:49.090
And then zeta of the odd
numbers are pretty much unknown.

00:43:49.090 --> 00:43:50.090
ROBERT GROSS: Completely

00:43:50.090 --> 00:43:50.965
AVNER ASH: Zeta of 3.

00:43:50.965 --> 00:43:51.670
Zeta of 5.

00:43:51.670 --> 00:43:53.480
Except there's one
thing that's known.

00:43:53.480 --> 00:43:57.520
That zeta of 3 is irrational.

00:43:57.520 --> 00:43:58.980
It's not a fraction.

00:43:58.980 --> 00:44:00.274
That's the only one, right?

00:44:00.274 --> 00:44:01.440
ROBERT GROSS: It's possible.

00:44:01.440 --> 00:44:02.860
AVNER ASH: Any zeta
of 5 is known also.

00:44:02.860 --> 00:44:03.190
ROBERT GROSS: Yeah.

00:44:03.190 --> 00:44:04.089
I'm not sure.

00:44:04.089 --> 00:44:05.130
But very little is known.

00:44:05.130 --> 00:44:06.970
And it's not hard to
go back to your office

00:44:06.970 --> 00:44:09.770
and get zeta of 3
computed to 100 places.

00:44:09.770 --> 00:44:12.860
Divide by pi cubed and
hope to spot something.

00:44:12.860 --> 00:44:14.070
We've all done it.

00:44:14.070 --> 00:44:15.960
And it's not anything.

00:44:15.960 --> 00:44:20.050
But maybe it's not pi cubed,
maybe it's pi to the 3/2.

00:44:20.050 --> 00:44:20.770
AVNER ASH: Oh.

00:44:20.770 --> 00:44:23.264
ROBERT GROSS: You could
play all afternoon and see.

00:44:23.264 --> 00:44:24.680
AVNER ASH: What I
was going to say

00:44:24.680 --> 00:44:28.140
though is if I
remember right, the way

00:44:28.140 --> 00:44:32.490
this guy proved that
zeta of 3 is irrational

00:44:32.490 --> 00:44:35.950
does have to do with the rate
of convergence of a series.

00:44:35.950 --> 00:44:36.700
ROBERT GROSS: Yes.

00:44:36.700 --> 00:44:39.158
AVNER ASH: So it's known that
if a series converges really,

00:44:39.158 --> 00:44:44.450
really rapidly a certain
type, then it cannot converge

00:44:44.450 --> 00:44:46.810
to a rational number.

00:44:46.810 --> 00:44:50.370
That's a kind of combination
of calculus and number theory.

00:44:50.370 --> 00:44:53.070
And now, the series
for zeta of 3

00:44:53.070 --> 00:44:55.380
itself doesn't have that
fast convergence property.

00:44:55.380 --> 00:44:57.860
But the [INAUDIBLE]
figure out some ways

00:44:57.860 --> 00:45:01.000
of manipulating it and
relating it to some very fast

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:02.110
quickly convergent series.

00:45:02.110 --> 00:45:02.790
Is that right?

00:45:02.790 --> 00:45:02.920
ROBERT GROSS: No.

00:45:02.920 --> 00:45:03.630
Entirely correct.

00:45:03.630 --> 00:45:04.296
AVNER ASH: Yeah.

00:45:04.296 --> 00:45:07.760
And so, that's the amazing
thing about this subject.

00:45:07.760 --> 00:45:10.360
You never know what
other part of mathematics

00:45:10.360 --> 00:45:15.940
is going to come in to be
useful in understanding

00:45:15.940 --> 00:45:18.800
just these properties of
these simple whole numbers

00:45:18.800 --> 00:45:20.605
and fractions.

00:45:20.605 --> 00:45:22.230
AUDIENCE: Regarding
the question of how

00:45:22.230 --> 00:45:25.750
do you interest people
in number theory.

00:45:25.750 --> 00:45:27.270
Given that unlike
in Hardy's times,

00:45:27.270 --> 00:45:30.370
there are actually applications
for number theory now.

00:45:30.370 --> 00:45:32.180
Is there a story
to tell there where

00:45:32.180 --> 00:45:34.840
people might be interested
in the applications

00:45:34.840 --> 00:45:37.250
and the number theory is
actually possible for people

00:45:37.250 --> 00:45:39.454
for laypeople to understand?

00:45:39.454 --> 00:45:40.120
AVNER ASH: Yeah.

00:45:40.120 --> 00:45:41.160
I think so.

00:45:41.160 --> 00:45:45.220
I mean I think that books
have been written about that.

00:45:45.220 --> 00:45:51.010
So if you look at the range
of books of mathematics

00:45:51.010 --> 00:45:56.880
for sort of the general public,
then there are different types.

00:45:56.880 --> 00:45:59.820
And one type is to concentrate
on these applications.

00:45:59.820 --> 00:46:01.890
And that's one good method.

00:46:01.890 --> 00:46:04.690
That's something we sort of
wanted to avoid in our book.

00:46:04.690 --> 00:46:08.260
Because we wanted to try to put
this out as something as very

00:46:08.260 --> 00:46:10.960
pure and theoretical.

00:46:10.960 --> 00:46:13.040
Just because that's
how we view it.

00:46:13.040 --> 00:46:16.300
But that's a good way to go.

00:46:16.300 --> 00:46:18.930
Another way is to talk
about the biographies

00:46:18.930 --> 00:46:20.370
of the mathematicians.

00:46:20.370 --> 00:46:21.990
That's pretty popular.

00:46:21.990 --> 00:46:24.130
And then, there are
quite a few books

00:46:24.130 --> 00:46:26.230
that just treat the
mathematics itself,

00:46:26.230 --> 00:46:28.210
but they usually start
at a higher level.

00:46:28.210 --> 00:46:31.620
And what we wanted to do
was to bring this down

00:46:31.620 --> 00:46:33.660
at least at the
beginning of each book.

00:46:33.660 --> 00:46:37.650
To bring it down to the lowest
possible level we could.

00:46:37.650 --> 00:46:40.210
The last one summing it up is
a little bit more difficult

00:46:40.210 --> 00:46:42.880
to actually.

00:46:42.880 --> 00:46:45.550
The algebra gets
heavy really fast.

00:46:45.550 --> 00:46:49.117
If you look at our first book,
"Fearless Symmetry", in a way

00:46:49.117 --> 00:46:51.450
that's harder to understand,
because it's more abstract.

00:46:51.450 --> 00:46:53.410
But in terms of the
math that is involved,

00:46:53.410 --> 00:46:55.060
the whole first eight
chapters involve

00:46:55.060 --> 00:46:58.930
nothing but addition,
subtraction, multiplication,

00:46:58.930 --> 00:47:01.190
and division.

00:47:01.190 --> 00:47:04.520
And yet, we're studying some
very interesting properties

00:47:04.520 --> 00:47:05.070
of numbers.

00:47:05.070 --> 00:47:10.710
Namely if you divide one
number by a prime number,

00:47:10.710 --> 00:47:12.080
you get a remainder.

00:47:12.080 --> 00:47:13.610
We're interested
in those remainders

00:47:13.610 --> 00:47:14.936
and how they fit together.

00:47:14.936 --> 00:47:17.060
And that's the beginning
of the story that leads on

00:47:17.060 --> 00:47:19.880
to these Galois
representations that

00:47:19.880 --> 00:47:23.027
are important in the proof
of Fermat's Last Theorem.

